abstract = {Summary Along the road, drivers come up against unexpected situations; for that reason static and dynamic road traffic signalization, besides real-time traffic and travel information (RTTI) systems, attempt to warn drivers about all the events happening on the road. This chapter explains the generic methodology of the intelligent information management system (IIMS) implemented in a traffic information system. The proposed methodology for the IIMS is validated with the onboard module's prototype. In this case, the inputs are the static and dynamic messages sent by beacons located along the infrastructure of the road, and then, received on the vehicle by the onboard module. The chapter describes the three functional models employed in the IIMS: the signal model, the interpretation model, and the representation model. The performance of the IIMS has been highlighted for different driving situations defined by different traffic density levels, meteorological conditions and vehicle speeds.}
